1. what is docker?
A. Docker is an open source containarization platform. It enables developers to package applications into containers.
I used docker to bulid the docker images and then write some docker files and using them to build docker images. once 
done using docker images to run docker containers and push them to registries.

2. How are containers different from virtual machines? 
A. Containers are very lightweight in nature bacause they don't have complete operating system but they have minimal 
system dependencies that are required to run application. 
But in virtual machines if created an EC2 instance we need application and install Java and need Kernal and system 
libraries and complete operating system. 
Ex:- If i'm running a Java application. I need some Java runtime dependency to run the Java application and i just need 
some system libraries that are mandatory to run application. So, these are the three things are basically defined to have 
this very lightweight nature.

3. what is the docker lifecycle? 
A. In my case what i usally do is I start writing a Docker file with the set of instructions that are required to run
the application. And once i feel the docker file is complete I will create Docker image using the docker CLI the command
is Docker build which essentially convert Docker file to Docker image. After that using Docker run command to execute 
container. And finally once container created push them to external registries like Docker Hub or quay.io.

4. what are the different docker components? 
A. The main Docker components are Docker Engine, Docker Client, Docker Daemon, Images, Containers, Registries, 
Dockerfiles, Volumes, and Networks, which together help build, store, deploy, and manage containerized applications.

5. what is the difference between docker COPY and docker ADD? 
A. Docker ADD can copy the files from a URL unlike Docker COPY which can COPY files from host system into the container.

6. what is the difference between CMD and ENTRYPOINT? 
A. CLI arguments using the Docker run command will override the aruguments specified using the CMD instruction.

Where as ENTRYPOINT instruction in the shell form will override additional arguments provided using CLI parameters or 
even through the CMD commands.

